column4:
You will see below a string member function called length(), which has an alias size()
In this class, I want you to exclusively use the **size()** version, not length()

Also, the text says that the string member function find returns -1 when the target is not found: *this is only partly true!* 
It returns a special number called npos, which can be cast to the integer -1. 
The **ONLY** correct way to test whether find has (or has not) found its target in a string is to compare the return value to this special value npos (to tell the compiler where to find the definition of npos, you have to write `string::npos`):
```
if (word.find(target) != string::npos) {...} //if target WAS found
if (word.find(target) == string::npos ) {...} //if target was NOT found
```

the text is more nuanced (correctly), and says that for vectors & strings known to be small, you should use value parameters.

You still must understand when to use the const modifier with reference parameters.

column4:
C uses the equal sign as the ASSIGNMENT operator.  This is very different than the equal sign used in your math classes.  In C the equal sign means store the value of the right side into the variable on the left side.  

It is possible to write C programs without ever using the assignment operator.  This is programming in a functional programming style and usually relies heavily on recursion (chapter 9).  Mathematicians favor functional programming.  

This class will focus on teaching C in its traditional, imperative style.  This how programming languages are more commonly used in engineering.

To specify the number of decimals for a floating point number, use the conversion specifier:
%.xf, where x is the replaced by the number of decimals you want. 

For example if you write %.2f, the number will be written with 2 decimals (convenient when writing dollar amount).

This chapter uses a common combination of a typedef declaration with a struct declaration. A typedef defines a new type name for an existing type. This material uses that combination exclusively and does not discuss typedef declarations separately.

column4:
In the Activity 5.3.1: Composition of relations, you can get the composition of R and S by making a list. Here is the process: 
1) List the point-to-point paths for R: (a,d), (d,c), (c,d), (b,b), (b,c).
2) List the point-to-point paths for S: (b,a), (b,d), (d,c).
3) Start with the pairs in R and see if there is a continuation of the path in S.
(a,d) to (d,c) yields (a,c)
(d,c) does not continue in S
(c,d) to (d,c) yields (c,c)
(b,b) to (b,a) yields (b,a)
(b,b) to (b,d) yields (b,d)
(b,c) does not continue in S
Therefore, the composition of R and S is (a,c), (c,c), (b,a), (b,d) 

If you are struggling with the graph in 5.3.3 Activity, use the same reasoning.

column4:
In previous programming courses (CIS 111 and 211) you have already covered many of the basic programming concepts. These concepts are mostly the same in Java that they were in Visual Basics or Python, but the syntax differs. 

Through the first 6 chapters we will mostly discuss differences between Python and Java syntax and a few more conceptual differences, and practice using Java syntax for problems using already known programming concepts. 

A good reference for a listing of differences can be found at http://anh.cs.luc.edu/331/notes/JavaVsPython.html.
column8: Columbia College CIS 212 Spring 2015: Programming in Java with Data Structures
Columbia College CIS 212 Spring 2015: Programming in Java with Data Structures

column4: A major difference between Python and Java is that Python is a dynamically typed language while Java is (mostly) statically typed. We will explain the \mostly\" in chapter 8 on inheritance right now you can think of Java as being statically typed. What does this mean? In Python you do not declare the type of a variable when it is declared. The type is defined when a value is stored in the variable and the type may change if a value of a different type is stored in the variable.  In Java you must declare the type of the variable when first defining it and the type of the variable cannot change once declared: it is static. So for example in Python: height = 50 in Java: int height = 50;"
column8: Columbia College CIS 212 Spring 2015: Programming in Java with Data Structures

column4:
In Java there is only one symbol for division (/).
If both operands are integers, then the result will be an integer, if at least one operand is a double then the result is a double.

For example,

3 / 2 gives 1

3.0 / 2 gives 1.5
column8: Columbia College CIS 212 Spring 2015: Programming in Java with Data Structures

column8: Programming in Python 3.3

column4: This section covers one important difference in the Python type int and the Java type int. As you might recall, in Python, int can be a large as we want. In Java, as in most other programming languages, int have a fixed range. If the content of variable can be in integer outside of this range then you can use the type long. But this type has also a fixed range, so if you need  a number outside of the range of long integers, yo must use a double, You will then use precision (number of significant digits).
column8: Columbia College CIS 212 Spring 2015: Programming in Java with Data Structures

column4:
Same relational operators in Java as in Python.
However in Java you may not \chain\" relational operators.  0<=x<= 3 is valid Python syntax  but it is invalid in Java. See section 3.4 how you express this relation. "
column8: Columbia College CIS 212 Spring 2015: Programming in Java with Data Structures

column4: The main difference in Java vs Python for multiple i-else branches is the use of \else if; instead of \"elif\"."
column8: Columbia College CIS 212 Spring 2015: Programming in Java with Data Structures

column4: Learn the Java logical operators for AND (&&), OR (||) and NOT(!).
column8: Columbia College CIS 212 Spring 2015: Programming in Java with Data Structures

column4: The for loop in Java has the most distinctive syntax compared to Python and it functions differently. It is mostly a different ways to express a counting while loop, but where the initialization of the variable, condition, and variable update are expressed in one statement at the top of the loop. This type of for loop does not allow to iterate through a list as the Python for loop did.
column8: Columbia College CIS 212 Spring 2015: Programming in Java with Data Structures

column4:
Arrays have a lot in common with Python lists , especially they have the same purpose of storing a list of related data and we use very similar syntax ([ ] and indices). However, arrays in Java have a few limitations compared to lists in Python:

- All elements in an array must have the same data type (we will slightly weaken this assertion when studying inheritance)
- Once created the number of elements in an array is fixed.
- There are no arrays methods.
- We cannot use negative indexing in Java.
column8: Columbia College CIS 212 Spring 2015: Programming in Java with Data Structures

column4:
The concept of method is the same in Java and in Python. In this chapter the methods will really work like Python functions because they are not really linked to objects. Starting in chapter 7, the Java method will be similar to the Python method.

Because we still write all our code in the class that contains the method main which will not be used to create an object, all our method, as main, will be declared as static. This means that the method can be called without an object being created.
column8: Columbia College CIS 212 Spring 2015: Programming in Java with Data Structures

column4: Python methods always return a value. If no explicit value is returned with a return statement then the value \none\" is returned. A method can return several values. The method header in Python does not indicate whether a value is returned. In Java  the header of a method must include a return type (before the name of the method): - void if no value is returned (method ends with return; or without return statement at all) - the data type of the return value (e.g. int  String boolean). If the return type is not void then a value of the correct type MUST be returned. - A Java method can return only one value. "
column8: Columbia College CIS 212 Spring 2015: Programming in Java with Data Structures

column4: The use of parameters is the same in Python and in Java. One difference is that, as for variables, the data type of parameters must be defined in the method definition.
column8: Columbia College CIS 212 Spring 2015: Programming in Java with Data Structures

column4:
The topic of method overloading is new as it does not exist in Python. Method overloading allows methods sharing the same name to be defined with different parameter lists. By different parameter list, we mean that the list of data types are different (keeping the same parameter types but different parameter names do not count). 
Note that methods with the same name must have the same return type.
column8: Columbia College CIS 212 Spring 2015: Programming in Java with Data Structures

column4: In this short chapter you will find a great deal of very useful information. You have the basics now of how to build a MATLAB function that can deal do a computation given inputs you supply, and give back to you the results (outputs) of the computation.  including flow charting. A widely used current methodology is \"incremental programming\". Put this idea firmly in your mind. INPUTS TO A FUNCTION... OUTPUTS FROM THE FUNCTION. That implies the steps for you to take when you first sit down to design a function then implement it. Programing is best thought of as TWO steps: design, then implement. Programming in fact is distinctly an engineering activity! The first step in design is to be sure you understand what inputs you will send a function, AND what outputs come back from the function. If you don't have a firm target in programming (or an engineering task) then you cannot hit that target!!T he second step in design is to get a framework for your implementation. That framework you will use from this point forward in 1101 is \incremental programming\". Over the years there have been many frameworks proposed to help programmers. Below you will find the authors of your ZYBook have one early step that is \"write a script\". Note as you read that they go on quickly to \"encapsulating that script in a function. In 1101 we have skipped that step of using a script. By the end of this term you will understand why. This chapter ends with an example focused on the \"green monster\" at Fenway Park in Boston. The example shows the steps in designing and implementing  starting with a given problem about the green monster and ending with a working program that solves the problem. My suggestion is you read this chapter once quickly for the BigPicture then go back and read for details. There is a lot of \"meat\" in this writing. Finally  as you read this chapter there are some things that will be unfamiliar to you. The code in Figure 4.1.4 has some lines that you will not initially understand because we have not covered them yet. Do not worry about the specifics here. Its the flow of the work that is important: the idea of how to develop code incrementally. "

In reference to division in Java, if both operands are integers then the remainder will be thrown away, so 
3/2 will evaluate to 1

However if one of the operands is a decimal number then the result will be a decimal number
so 3.0/2 or 3/2.0 or 3.0/2.0 will all evaluate to 1.5

Referring to Figure 6.10.2, why is this? It will make more sense after reading section 6.11 Scope Resolution. Briefly, when only accessing, not assigning, a variable, Python will try to find the variable's object, which may be global. When assigning a variable a value, Python assumes it is local, and if not already in use, will make a new object - unless the variable is declared global, in which case Python will use the global variable.

Also, you have been, or will be, introduced to declaring your main program as a function called main(). This will force you to declare global variables outside the scope of all functions, including main*). In this way, the use of global variables will be done explicitly and for good reason.

Processing strings is a powerful and intrinsic feature of Python. Much processing that you might do involves manipulating string data, for example, reformatting data files so that the data can be input to various programs and packages. Being able to do this is not only valuable for your own work but also provides you with a skill that is valuable to others. This applies to all disciplines not only STEM. In fact you might argue it is more valuable to other disciplines. For example, my own work in corpus linguistics with the English Department is making excellent use of string manipulation. I.e., much, if not most, computing does not involve solving math and science problems.

For now you have only seen user input, but when we get to file processing, you will see more the usefulness of these techniques as you may read in files with large numbers of data points.

Converting from small to a large format integer: the processor will do the right thing always:
uint8_t a = -1;   //  = 1111 1111
uint16_t b = a;  //  =  1111 1111 1111 1111

Likewise, converting from large to small format, the system will attempt to do the right thing.  We only lose when we try to convert a number that is too small or large in magnitude to fit into the small format.

Exercise 6.17.1 involves doing some algebra to get the right answer. In keeping with what I've said so far in the class, I'm going to give you the formula you need to derive this part.

The gas equation PV=nRT is the equation you need to use, but you only have some of the parts. You have P, n, R, and T and need to solve for V. Algebraically, the resulting equation is:

P = (nRT)/V

All you need to do is implement that in code.

my_list.sort(reverse=True)

This 'parameter' for the sort method allows your list to be sorted in reverse order.  True is a boolean value.

column4: For Activity 5.4.7 Calculating a Factorial.  I would suggest you research what a factorial is and what the equation does.  The reason why a loop construct makes sense is due to the nature of the equation.  If you look at what is provided you can see that the equation requires a counter.  That is why a loop makes sense.  You don't have to keep typing in n - 1, n - 2, etc.  Additionally when testing know that the provided test data may be unclear.  The program needs to input, for instance the value 5.  The output should be (if the equation is correct), the value 120.
